instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "The system is organized around a Digital Shadow Reference Model expressed as a UML class diagram that defines three core concepts – Asset, Model, and Processing – together with Data Traces and their provenance associations. A concrete digital shadow is realized by mapping concrete elements (e.g., specific sensor data sources, simulation or data‑calculation models, and software processing components) onto these reference concepts, thereby forming a conforming class diagram. The architecture follows a component‑and‑connector style typical of MBSE: assets represent physical CPS elements, models encode engineering, simulation, or calculation logic, and processing components consume input data traces, invoke the associated models, and produce new output traces. Traceability is maintained via the 'originates‑from' association, allowing transitive back‑tracking from any data trace to its generating processing component, input traces, and involved models. The overall orchestration is defined through MBSE modeling languages such as SysML (including internal block diagrams and state machines) and ADLs (e.g., ACME, AADL, MontiArc), enabling hierarchical decomposition from requirements through functional and logical architectures down to the product/technical layer. Resource management and system‑wide coordination rely on the explicit mapping between concrete realizations and reference concepts, supporting heterogeneous stakeholder integration and multi‑tool interoperability."
]

instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "The DT lifecycle described follows an MBSE‑driven progression through successive abstraction layers: (1) requirements modelling, (2) functional architecture, (3) logical architecture, and (4) product/technical (physical) layer. During development, a reference Digital Shadow model is instantiated, then a concrete realization (concretization) is performed, yielding a digital twin that embodies the same concepts with concrete elements. Transition between stages is managed by mapping associations (e.g., originates‑from) that preserve traceability of data traces and processing components. Governance relies on the conformance relation defined for the reference class diagram, ensuring that each concrete model adheres to the reference model."
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "Model fidelity is ensured by traceability and verification of the transformation chain from high‑level SysML specifications to lower‑level simulation or executable models (e.g., SysML → Simulink, SysML → C++). Validation consists of comparing simulation outputs with measured data traces collected from the physical system; deviations are used to assess model accuracy. The approach emphasizes verification of model transformations to guarantee consistency, and relies on explicit traceability links to support quality assurance of both models and the underlying data."
]
